<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="515" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,873,1474]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">
This subspecies was based on 
<specimenCount box="[521,674,874,898]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">two syntypes</specimenCount>
(shells) from “Quickborn, near Okahandja, South West Africa” [
<collectingCountry box="[157,260,909,934]" name="Namibia" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Namibia</collectingCountry>
] (
<bibRefCitation author="Hewitt, J." box="[283,430,909,934]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="283 - 357" refId="ref12349" refString="Hewitt, J. (1935) Some new forms of batrachians and reptiles from South Africa. Records of the Albany Museum, 4, 283 - 357, plates XXVII - XXXVI." type="journal article" year="1935">Hewitt 1935</bibRefCitation>
: p. 338). Actually, Quickborn is a farm approximately halfway between Okahandja and Otjiwarongo, 
<collectingCountry box="[311,411,945,970]" name="Namibia" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Namibia</collectingCountry>
. Following 
<bibRefCitation author="Mertens, R." box="[553,726,945,970]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="139 - 142" refId="ref12650" refString="Mertens, R. (1937) Bemerkungen uber die Rassen von Pelomedusa subrufa (La Cepede). Zoologischer Anzeiger, 117, 139 - 142." type="journal article" year="1937">Mertens (1937</bibRefCitation>
: p. 139) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Loveridge, A." box="[889,1086,945,970]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="467 - 524" refId="ref12616" refString="Loveridge, A. (1941) Revision of the African terrapin [sic] of the family Pelomedusidae. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 88, 467 - 524." type="journal article" year="1941">Loveridge (1941</bibRefCitation>
: p. 474), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1935" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="galeata" subSpecies="damarensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Pelomedusa galeata damarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was later synonymized with the nominotypical subspecies of the helmeted terrapin, if the species was regarded as polytypic. 
<bibRefCitation author="Herrmann, H. - W. &amp; Branch, W. R." box="[421,743,1017,1042]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="94 - 115" refId="ref12286" refString="Herrmann, H. - W. &amp; Branch, W. R. (2013) Fifty years of herpetological research in the Namib Desert and Namibia with an updated and annotated species checklist. Journal of Arid Environments, 93, 94 - 115. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jaridenv. 2012.05.003" type="journal article" year="2013">Herrmann &amp; Branch (2013</bibRefCitation>
: p. 102) suggested that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1935" box="[1032,1405,1017,1042]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="galeata" subSpecies="damarensis">
<emphasis box="[1032,1405,1017,1042]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Pelomedusa galeata damarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically distinctive and may deserve specific recognition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,873,1474]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">
The 
<specimenCount box="[250,398,1090,1114]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">two syntypes</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1935" box="[437,801,1089,1114]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="galeata" subSpecies="damarensis">
<emphasis box="[437,801,1089,1114]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Pelomedusa galeata damarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are now in the collection of the Port Elizabeth Museum (PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[228,316,1125,1150]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14953" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14953</accessionNumber>
– 
<accessionNumber box="[331,421,1125,1150]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14954" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14954</accessionNumber>
) and were examined for the present study. Whilst PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[1082,1170,1125,1150]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14953" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14953</accessionNumber>
is perfectly preserved, parts of the epidermal scutes on the right carapacial margin of PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[935,1024,1161,1186]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14954" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14954</accessionNumber>
are missing. We designate herewith the better preserved specimen PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[564,652,1197,1222]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14953" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14953</accessionNumber>
(
<figureCitation box="[670,740,1197,1222]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[190,1375,226,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-75@16.[167,1419,193,1842]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Dorsal and ventral views of the lectotype of Pelomedusa galeata damarensis Hewitt, 1935 (PEM R14953, adult male, straight carapacial length 14.0 cm; top) and of the holotype of Pelomedusa galeata devilliersi Hewitt, 1935 (PEM R14962, adult female, straight carapacial length 19.24 cm; bottom). Scale bars, 3 cm. Photos: W.R. Branch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915078/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, top) as 
<typeStatus box="[839,942,1197,1222]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1935" box="[982,1348,1197,1222]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="galeata" subSpecies="damarensis">
<emphasis box="[982,1348,1197,1222]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Pelomedusa galeata damarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Tissue for genetic investigation was extracted from both type specimens. From PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[1048,1139,1233,1258]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14953" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14953</accessionNumber>
, 252 bp of the 12S rRNA gene could be successfully sequenced, whereas only 35 bp of the 12S rRNA gene and 319 bp of the cyt 
<emphasis box="[1360,1374,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">b</emphasis>
gene could be generated for PEM 
<accessionNumber box="[474,563,1305,1330]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/R14954" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">R14954</accessionNumber>
(
<tableCitation box="[576,663,1305,1330]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="4.[147,233,594,616]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 2. Pelomedusa type specimens studied genetically. Lengths of successfully sequenced mtDNA fragments indicated. For GenBank accession numbers, see Table S1. The cyt b sequence of ZFMK 17076 was generated by Wong et al. (2010). For museum acronyms, see Table 1." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF60661ECF54102818C7E96BFBB0FD26" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" tableUuid="DF60661ECF54102818C7E96BFBB0FD26">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,873,1474]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">
In phylogenetic analyses (
<figureCitation box="[504,574,1341,1366]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1100,1122]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,201,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-427@5.[151,1436,195,1080]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Maximum Likelihood tree for Pelomedusa, based on 1848 bp of mitochondrial DNA (12S, cyt b, ND4+tRNAs), rooted with Pelusios sinuatus. The tree topology completely matches the one inferred by Bayesian analyses. Numbers along nodes indicate bootstrap support and Bayesian posterior probabilities greater than 50 or 0.95, respectively (not shown for some terminal clades with short branches). Sample codes are voucher numbers; see Table S1 for explanation. Name-bearing types (red) and paralectotypes or topotypic samples (blue) highlighted. On the right, mitochondrial lineages of Vargas-Ramírez et al. (2010) indicated. No topotypic material of Pelomedusa galeata orangensis Hewitt, 1935 could be sequenced. However, the lost holotype is thought to come from the vicinity of Kimberley (South Africa) and all South African samples belong to lineage IX, so it can be concluded that Pelomedusa galeata orangensis represents the same lineage. Inset: Helmeted terrapin from the Addo Elephant National Park, South Africa. Photo: M. Gregorič." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915066/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the sequences of both 
<typeStatus box="[870,918,1342,1366]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">type</typeStatus>
specimens are embedded with high support within lineage VIII of 
<bibRefCitation author="Vargas-Ramirez, M. &amp; Vences, M. &amp; Branch, W. R. &amp; Daniels, S. R. &amp; Glaw, F. &amp; Hofmeyr, M. D. &amp; Kuchling, G. &amp; Maran, J. &amp; Papenfuss, T. J. &amp; Siroky, P. &amp; Vieites, D. R. &amp; Fritz, U." box="[405,734,1377,1402]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="428 - 440" refId="ref13781" refString="Vargas-Ramirez, M., Vences, M., Branch, W. R., Daniels, S. R., Glaw, F., Hofmeyr, M. D., Kuchling, G., Maran, J., Papenfuss, T. J., Siroky, P., Vieites, D. R. &amp; Fritz, U. (2010) Deep genealogical lineages in the widely distributed African helmeted terrapin: evidence from mitochondrial and nuclear DNA (Testudines: Pelomedusidae: Pelomedusa subrufa). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 56, 428 - 440. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2010.03.019" type="journal article" year="2010">
Vargas-Ramírez 
<emphasis box="[592,649,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">et al.</emphasis>
(2010)
</bibRefCitation>
. The oldest available name for lineage VIII is 
<taxonomicName authority="Bonnaterre, 1789" authorityName="Bonnaterre" authorityYear="1789" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subrufa">
<emphasis box="[1257,1435,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Testudo subrufa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bonnaterre" box="[151,353,1413,1438]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" refId="ref11147" refString="Bonnaterre, [P. J.] (1789) Tableau encyclopedique et methodique des trois regnes de la nature. Erpetologie. Panckoucke, Hotel de Thou, Paris, xxviii + 70 + (1) pp., 35 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 59326" type="book" year="1789">Bonnaterre, 1789</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see above), rendering 
<taxonomicName authority="Hewitt, 1935 a" authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1935" box="[649,1225,1413,1438]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="galeata" subSpecies="damarensis">
<emphasis box="[649,1028,1413,1438]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="515">Pelomedusa galeata damarensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hewitt, J." box="[1044,1198,1413,1438]" pageId="14" pageNumber="515" pagination="283 - 357" refId="ref12349" refString="Hewitt, J. (1935) Some new forms of batrachians and reptiles from South Africa. Records of the Albany Museum, 4, 283 - 357, plates XXVII - XXXVI." type="journal article" year="1935">Hewitt, 1935</bibRefCitation>
a
</taxonomicName>
subjective junior synonym of the previous name, if lineage VIII should be regarded as taxonomically distinct.
</paragraph>
